Project 2D¶

Barbod Khaleghi

Scientific Question: How structurally similar is the envelope, E, protein of SARS-CoV-2 virus compared to that of the SARS-CoV virus?¶

Beginning in late 2019, the COVID-19 pandemic began in the world and has plagued all countries since. To better understand the coronavirus that is causing this, I explored protein structures of such coronaviruses. SARS-CoV is a coronavirus known to cause Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome, or SARS. While SARS is known to cause many of the same respiratory symptoms as COVID-19, it differs as it has much milder effects and has never reached epidemic or pandemic status. SARS has been around since 2003, showcasing how the species of coronaviruses themselves have been around for a while. The novel SARS-CoV-2, on the other hand, has emerged fairly recently. The SARS-CoV-2 coronavirus has been found to be the to cause the disease Covid-19 and is the direct cause of this pandemic.

To better understand the similarities between the two diseases, I needed to explore the structural proteins. Excluding the spike proteins present, I decided to explore the structures of the envelope proteins. Envelope, or E, proteins are small proteins that are involved in the virus through playing a role in assembly, envelope formation, and pathogenesis. Specifically, in the SARS-CoV-2 virus, the E protein has been found to couple with the membrane protein and form the viral envelope. Using the U.S. National Library of Medicine (https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/Structure/SARS-CoV-2.html), it was found that the envelope protein for the SARS-CoV-2 coronavirus was 7K3G and the envelope protein for the SARS-CoV coronavirus was 5X29.

Scientific Hypothesis: If the SARS-CoV-2 envelope protein, found from the publically available databases, is drastically structurally unique, then there will not be any distinct notable similarities between its structure that of the envelope protein from SARS-CoV.¶

After learning about the envelope proteins in SARS-COV-2 and SARS-CoV, it was found that their structures are 7K3G and 5X29 respectively. Using this, I explored the PDB database (RCSB: https://www.rcsb.org/) and found the structures. Once found, I download the fasta files to help me store their amino acid sequences and the pdb files to store their structures. These files were used throughout.

The first bioinformatics analysis method I used was pairwise sequence alignment. This is the method by which regions of similarity are found between two protein sequences. In doing so, I am able to better understand if there is any indication in there being a structural relationship between the two envelope proteins. The second method used was homology modeling and structural bioinformatics. This focuses on the analysis of the 3D models of the proteins structures. Using PyMol and nglview, a clear understanding of the protein's structure is presented. Creating an overlay between the two proteins, one is able to understand target differences.

The third and fourth methods are sequence logos and 3D protein measurements. Sequence logos is created from the aligned sequences and is a plotting method by which the sequence conservation of the amino acids is represented. This helps to analyze the protein sequences together. The 3D protein measurements entail a variety of measurements explaining distance between key parts of the protein that can help to establish relationship between varying proteins.

Pairwise Sequence Alignment¶

To begin, I performed pairwise sequence alignment. Here, I was able to get both the SARS-CoV-2 and SARS-CoV envelope proteins and analyze their fasta files that encapsulates their sequences. To do this, I first had to load in two packages, pairwise2 and SeqIO, from biopython. Pairwise2 is a package that is able to create global and local alignments between two sequences presented. Using such methods, it finds the best subsequences and aligns them based on their best alignment. The second package, SeqIO is used for the fasta filesl. This package is able to provide an interface in which it can input and ouput these sequence files. This is used to be able to import and work with the fasta files of each of th enevelope protein sequences. There is a third package imported later called format_alignment from the bio.pairwise2 module. This will be used later to help provide a formatting method for the alignment. Using this formatting method, the results are able to be visualized better through formatting standard. After the proper packages are imported, the sequences are saved as cov2 and cov respectively with the SeqIO.read function. Once the variables are created, the pairwise2.align.globalxx function is used from the pairwise2 package. This creates a global alignments using the sequences stored. This is a global variable that can access vastly throughout the entirety of the program. The rest of the code is also global code, as they can be called from anywhere in the notebook. Moving on, I created a for loop that helps to print out the individual alignment objects obtained from the alignment created. To finish, using the formatting method imported, the data is formatted to be easier to visualize.

Homology Modeling and Structural Bioinformatics¶

PyMOL¶

PyMOL is a program created that presented visual 3D representations of various molecular protein structures based off of their codes. It provides an assisted interface that can be used in various ways to provide analysis of the structures. Below are the PyMOL images of the 7K3G and 5X29, SARS-CoV-2 and SARS-CoV, in that order. I have included this for a basic visual, seperating the colors based on the chains of the protein. This sets as a precedent before overlaying both of the structures to analyze for similarities.

7K3G¶

5X29¶

To compare both of the structures, I aligned them over each other based off matching chains. I did this using "align 7K3G,5X29" command. This overlayed the matching chains over one another to analyze matches. As can be seen below, there are many overlapping sections which proves that there is some form of similarity in the structure of the proteins that can be tested form using 3D protein measurements later. In this case, the blue color is the 5X29 protein and the green color is the 7K3G.

Here, I am using structural bioinformatics method of using nglview to showcase the structures of the envelope proteins. I imported two packages for this. First package was the Bio.PDB. This package is effective in being used for analyzing pdb structures and overall accessing such information. This will ultimately be used to activated the parser. The second package was nglview. This is a package used to access databases containing protein structures and print out 3D visualizations of such. To import this pip install nglview must be done first, but is already a part of my computer program so I did not include it here. They work in coordination with the pdb files. After importing the packages, the PDBparser command is ran as an empty function of be used in getting the desired structures. Using the parser, the .get_structure function is used to get both of the pdb's and store as variables of the cov2 and cov respectively. With thise variables, nv.show_biopython is used to display the structure. The parser command here is a global variable as is used in various parts, whiloe the rest are local pertaining to direct block.

In [81]:
#importing Bio.PDB
from Bio.PDB import *
#importing nglview
import nglview as nv
In [82]:
#creating the parser varibale by running empty function
parser = PDBParser()
In [83]:
#saving the pdb structure for SARS-CoV-2
cov2_structure = parser.get_structure("7K3G", "7k3g.pdb")
#saving the pdb structure file for SARS-CoV
cov_structure = parser.get_structure("5x29", "5x29.pdb")
In [84]:
#using nglview to display 3D structure of SARS-CoV-2 envelope protein
view = nv.show_biopython(cov2_structure)
view
In [85]:
#using nglview to display 3D structure of SARS-CoV envelope protein
view = nv.show_biopython(cov_structure)
view

Sequence Logos¶

Next, I am trying to develop the sequence logos. This is an example provided by the professor as my fasta files were incompatible with the sequence logos process. Sequence logos can be used to analyze sequence conservation of amino acids. This is a graphical representation based of the alignments of sequences. To begin, the logomaker package must first be installed. This is done below and is used to create the sequence logos. Logomaker seems to be a complex system method that helps to graphically illustrate the amino acid products. After installing logomaker, 4 packages must be imported. First, I imported numpy as np which can help with many of the mathematical analysis in python and creating functions based off such analysis. Second, I imported pandas as pd. This is useful to create a pandas dataframe and use such dataframe function to analyze the sequences in such manner. Next, I am importing mstplotlib.pyplot. This can be helpful to be used in creating plots in python and has many functions to create a variety of graphical representations. Lastly, I am importing the installed logomaker as lm. This is the program that will allow the creation of the sequence logos. The function library this provides analyses sequence alignments to form these sequence logos along the other imported packages. To do this, the alignment is used and turned into a functionality matrix. Using the dataframe created, we are then able to form a graphical representation of the amino acids present and their positions using the imported packages, especially logomaker.

3D Protein Measurements¶

3D protein measurements are different analytical methods of observing the structure of the protein based on mathetimatical variety between distances. One measurement is the distance between two alpha carbons based on the locations of the residues of a protein structure. To do this, the same imported packages as above were used such as numpy and PDBparser but were not included in the code as I did not want to included repeated code. First, I analyzed the SARS-CoV-2 structure by using the pdb parser function to access the protein. Using that, I assigned another variable for residues that utulized the .get_residues function to isolate the residues of the SARS-CoV-2 protein. I then seperated the two alpha carbons analyzes for a pair of residuals created to analyze the distance between them using the function provided in the print command below. This same process was used for the SARS-CoV protein. Doing so, I discovered that they have very similar distances between alpha carbons on their residuals with only a 0.005 difference. Then, for further analysis, I looked at the secondary structures of the proteins. In doing so, I looked for the fraction of amino acids found in each of the three classical secondary structures, alpha helixes, turns, and beta sheets (in that order). To do this in its entirety, I had to import the protein analysis package from bio.sequtils.protparam module. This enables a reading of the sequence reading and a protein analysis using the analyzed sequences. Before, I presented these percents on the secondary structure, I looked at the overall amino acid content by using the .get_amino_acids_percent() function from the protein analysis package. Using this, I was able to look at the amino acids present and understand what they were before seeing their distribution. Then, analyzing the secondary structure, I used the .secondary_structure_fraction() function in order to understand the amount of amino acids in each of the secondary structures. Doing so, I saw that they had no distinct similarities between the two envelope proteins. These are all global variables as they are not constricted by the limits of only one created function and can be used to analyze from any variable.

Conclusion¶

According to the bioinformatics methods analyzed above, it is evident that my hypothesis was incorrect in that there are indeed structural similarities between the envelope proteins of both SARS-CoV-2 and SARS-CoV, 7K3G and 5X29. The pairwise alignment and sequence logos methods allowed a demonstration of the alignment occuring between the two sequences and adequately assembled their two sequences together. Looking at the structural bioinformatics aspect, using the PyMOL aligning model, it is clear that there are similarities between the structures of the two proteins. As seen in the model, the area toward the middle contains distinct chains that are overlaying on one another between the proteins and somewhat formed a connection that exemplifies a given similiarity in that sense. There are, however, differences in the chains that branch away forming a circle around the middle area, proving the sequences to not be identical. Even though this is the case, there is a pletitude of visual evidence that at least some similarity does exist between the two, in that middle area especially. After analyzing the visual models, I turned my attention to the 3D protein measurements to help better understand the structure differences. I tried looking at the differences in their secondary structure amino acid distribution but was met with only distinct differences between the proteins that exist. Looking further, I also decided to analyze the distance between alpha carbons in a pair of residuals from each protein. This provided a great similarity between the two as the distances seemed to be coorespondant. Looking at each result, SARS-CoV-2 envelope protein had a distance of 3.8015 between alpha carbons of the residuals, while SARS-CoV had a distance of 3.8067. This is only a 0.005 difference and proves a direct similarity. All in all, the information found here provides a direct link between two coronavirus that lead to very similar respiratory diseases. There is a clear similarity between them but they are not identical. To further examine why the SARS-CoV-2 virus has been a deadly virus, reaching pandemic level while the SARS-CoV virus of the past as not, I would look into the spike protein analysis on the SARS-CoV-2 virus to better understand its structure.
